word_summaries_chapter_102:
  102:1:1:"The first word of verse (102:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">lām hā wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">ل ه و</span>). The attached object pronoun is second person masculine plural."
  102:1:2:"The second word of verse (102:1) is a form III masculine verbal noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verbal noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">kāf thā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ك ث ر</span>)."
  102:2:1:"The first word of verse (102:2) is an inceptive particle."
  102:2:2:"The second word of verse (102:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and subject pronoun. The perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is second person masculine plural. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">zāy wāw rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ز و ر</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">التاء</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  102:2:3:"The third word of verse (102:2) is a masculine plural noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf bā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق ب ر</span>)."
  102:3:1:"The first word of verse (102:3) is an aversion particle."
  102:3:2:"The second word of verse (102:3) is a future particle."
  102:3:3:"The third word of verse (102:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and subject pronoun. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is second person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn lām mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ل م</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">الواو</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  102:4:1:"The first word of verse (102:4) is a coordinating conjunction."
  102:4:2:"The second word of verse (102:4) is an aversion particle."
  102:4:3:"The third word of verse (102:4) is a future particle."
  102:4:4:"The fourth word of verse (102:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and subject pronoun. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is second person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn lām mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ل م</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">الواو</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  102:5:1:"The first word of verse (102:5) is an aversion particle."
  102:5:2:"The second word of verse (102:5) is a conditional particle."
  102:5:3:"The third word of verse (102:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and subject pronoun. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is second person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn lām mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ل م</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">الواو</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  102:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (102:5) is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn lām mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ل م</span>)."
  102:5:5:"The fifth word of verse (102:5) is a masculine singular noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">yā qāf nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ي ق ن</span>)."
  102:6:1:"The first word of verse (102:6) is divided into 3 morphological segments. An emphatic prefix, verb and emphatic suffix. The prefixed particle <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"surely\" or \"indeed\" and is used to add emphasis. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is second person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā hamza yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر أ ي</span>). The suffixed emphatic particle is known as the <i class=\"ab\">nūn</i> of emphasis (<span class=\"at\">نون التوكيد</span>)."
  102:6:2:"The second word of verse (102:6) is a feminine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">jīm ḥā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ج ح م</span>)."
  102:7:1:"The first word of verse (102:7) is a coordinating conjunction."
  102:7:2:"The second word of verse (102:7) is divided into 4 morphological segments. An emphatic prefix, verb, emphatic suffix and object pronoun. The prefixed particle <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"surely\" or \"indeed\" and is used to add emphasis. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is second person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā hamza yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر أ ي</span>). The suffixed emphatic particle is known as the <i class=\"ab\">nūn</i> of emphasis (<span class=\"at\">نون التوكيد</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person feminine singular."
  102:7:3:"The third word of verse (102:7) is a feminine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn yā nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ي ن</span>)."
  102:7:4:"The fourth word of verse (102:7) is a masculine singular noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">yā qāf nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ي ق ن</span>)."
  102:8:1:"The first word of verse (102:8) is a coordinating conjunction."
  102:8:2:"The second word of verse (102:8) is divided into 3 morphological segments. An emphatic prefix, verb and emphatic suffix. The prefixed particle <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"surely\" or \"indeed\" and is used to add emphasis. The passive imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is second person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">sīn hamza lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">س أ ل</span>). The suffixed emphatic particle is known as the <i class=\"ab\">nūn</i> of emphasis (<span class=\"at\">نون التوكيد</span>)."
  102:8:3:"The third word of verse (102:8) is a time adverb."
  102:8:4:"The fourth word of verse (102:8) is a preposition."
  102:8:5:"The fifth word of verse (102:8) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn ʿayn mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ع م</span>)."